<DOCNO> AP901007-0007 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
fabled in history but reviled today japans 
military leads the life of a secondclass citizen in this country 
where pacifism is not just a policy but a constitutional vow 
on sunday the self defense forces celebrated their 36th 
anniversary on a remote parade ground in asaka just north of 
tokyo the field bristled with the latest surfacetoair missiles 
tanks and other hightech weapons 
finance minister ryutaro hashimoto reviewing the troops 
assured them the nation stood behind their noble and important 
mission 
but on the streets of japan soldiers are often harassed as 
tax thiefs and in parliament the militarys voice is rarely 
heard despite the governing conservative partys push for a more 
active military role overseas in response to the persian gulf 
crisis 
indeed custom dictates that top military officials are not even 
invited to government policymaking meetings an audience with the 
emperor an honor treasured by new cabinet ministers is denied the 
chairman of the joint chiefs of staff 
sentiment here is still very strong 45 years after the war 
people detest things military said masashi nishihara a 
professor at japans defense academy even today the sdf does 
not make its views known officially 
tomohisa sakanaka a defense expert at aoyama gakuin university 
said political leaders are very scared of treating the military 
in an honored way theyd prefer to disengage them from the 
mainstream 
the stated mission of the militarys 275000 ground sea and air 
forces is the defense of japan and its sea lanes to a distance of 
1000 miles ostensibly against communist aggression in the far 
east 
the militarys 1220 tanks 55 destroyers 14 submarines and 320 
jet fighters are prevented from going farther by japans 
constitution which bars the use of force overseas the 
allvolunteer force was formed as part of the us security 
umbrella which includes about 50000 troops stationed here 
but the militarys mission was conceived in 1954 when the cold 
war was in full swing and japan had barely recovered from the ashes 
of world war ii 
today this resourcepoor country whose status as the worlds 
no 2 economy rests on a farflung network of rawmaterial imports 
faces the task of redefining what constitutes its national 
security 
the danger at home has receded in the face of soviet 
liberalization and japans new detente with china and north korea 
and dangers abroad are growing as signaled by the crisis in the 
middle east from where japan gets 70 percent of its oil 
as a result parliament will be hotly debating this fall just 
how far selfdefense should extend prime minister toshiki kaifu 
has proposed sending a smal number of noncombat troops to the 
persian gulf under the un flag and he insists the people will 
listen to me about the need to expand the militarys mission 
hed better have a good explanation 
in museums and television dramas the brave samurai of 
yesteryear is as popular as ever but modern japan remains haunted 
by darker preoccupations the nations more than 1000 years of 
military rule when ruthless warlords dominated civil 
administrators and emperor alike 
it happened once too often in the 1930s militarists again rose 
up and broke free of civilian control shattering japans shaky 
first attempt at constitutional democracy the result was the 
catastrophic pacific war the only defeat suffered by this 
intensely proud nation on its own soil 
japans surrender brought a psychological aboutface the 
usimposed constitution that forever forbids war remains an 
unyielding article of faith here 
perhaps the wars most enduring legacy though was that it 
erased from many japanese minds the idea of military power as a 
necessity 
a whole generation of japanese has grown up without any 
consciousness of the need for military strength said minoru 
hirano a vice principal at a tokyo high school 
much of the blame for that can be laid on the nations 
educators who were deeply shamed over the role they played in 
indoctrinating prewar youth to die for the emperor said sakanaka 
the defense expert 
today the main slogan of the powerful nikkyoso teachers union 
remains never send our students to the battlefield again 
other asian nations still bitter over japans brutal wartime 
incursions into china korea the philippines and other countries 
view the slightest rumblings of japanese militarism with the same 
fear that europe has traditionally felt toward a resurgent germany 
almost all experts here agree that a newly aggressive japan is 
unlikely despite its ranking among the worlds top five military 
spenders at 31 billion a year 
surveys since the aug 2 iraqi invasion of kuwait consistently 
show that more than 60 percent of japanese oppose an overseas role 
for the military 
because weve been at peace for so long and no ones conscious 
of any danger none of us really think about the self defense 
forces at all said manabu watanabe 21 one of a group of 
college students munching hamburgers at a wendys in tokyo 
partly because of such sentiments officials acknowledge 
difficulty in annually recruiting 20000 new soldiers from japans 
population more than 120 million people thats despite starting 
wages of about 880 a month 21 percent higher than for us 
soldiers 
moreover some who join are stung by us criticism that japan 
has shirked its global responsibilities by sending money but few 
men to the persian gulf 
we cant be full members of the free world society said an 
officer quoted recently in local news if we do not shed blood to 
protect world security 
</TEXT>
