rogerson who works at a local shop n save supermarket was 
arrested that evening and charged with manslaughter but the charge 
was dropped the next month after a grand jury concluded his actions 
were neither criminally negligent nor criminally reckless 
the finding triggered a flood of letters to newspapers 
some writers called for more stringent laws to replace the 
current statute prohibiting the use of firearms within 300 feet of 
an occupied residence the legislature rejected the suggestion 
other writers said wood should have worn bright clothing because 
it was deer season some critics even suggested she was at fault 
for wearing white mittens contending they could have been mistaken 
for the underside of a deers tail 
some letters hinted that because she was from away a term 
used to describe people from other states she was ignorant of 
maines hunting practices and traditions 
the state attorney generals office reopened the case after a 
television station reported that a nephew of rogersons lawyer had 
served on the first grand jury the second grand jury indicted 
rogerson in december 
rogerson who is married and has three children faces up to 20 
years in prison if he is convicted 
vafiades would not allow his client to be interviewed but 
vafiades said rogerson feels he is the target because of the 
circumstances of this case 
wood moved from maine shortly after the first grand jury cleared 
rogerson and now lives in iowa with his daughters who are about 
to celebrate their third birthday 
he said he doesnt have high hopes for a conviction part of 
the community has already voiced strong support for the man who 
killed my wife he said 
