<TEXT>
a 10mile string of about 10 new volcanoes 
has been discovered on the ocean floor about 300 miles off the 
oregon coast scientists said 
the volcanoes some more than 100 feet high and a halfmile 
wide were spotted by scientists studying maps and photographs of 
the sea floor along the juan de fuca ridge which runs north and 
south off the washington and oregon coasts 
they were formed within the past decade said robert embley a 
marine geologist with the national oceanic and atmospheric 
administrations pacific marine environmental laboratory in 
newport 
photographs taken last year and topographic surveys in august 
showed new cones that did not appear in 1981 surveys in august 
scientists using the submersible alvin found fresh lava flows 
extending into and over a large fracture in the sea floor 
the volcanoes are not continuous but they are difficult to 
count because some have joined together embley said in a story 
published sunday in the oregonian they are not huge like mount 
st helens but they can be described more as volcanic mounds 
embley made the discovery with william chadwick a research 
associate with oregon state university and christopher fox a 
remotesensing specialist with noaa the researchers work at the 
hatfield marine science center 
this is a big step embley said its the first time we 
can actually see a seafloor spreading event im sure were going 
to learn a lot about how eruptions occur and what happens during 
these events 
lava comes up from magma chambers beneath such midocean ridges 
where the sea floor forms and spreads 
embley said the volcanoes are about 1 miles deep on the crest 
of the juan de fuca ridge where the juan de fuca and the pacific 
tectonic plates form the juan de fuca plate creeps eastward toward 
the continent from the ridge while the pacific plate moves 
westward the plates are huge slabs of the earths crus 
the volcanoes may be related to gigantic bursts of hot 
mineralrich water called megaplumes embley said the 
megaplumes were discovered by noaa scientists in 1986 and 1987 one 
measured about 12 miles in diameter and 2000 feet thick 
</TEXT>
