the populist freedom party capitalizing 
on widespread popular discontent over bureaucracy and corruption 
made strong gains in parliamentary elections sunday 
the governing socialists slightly increased their representation 
and offered to form a new coalition government with the 
conservative peoples party which lost ground in the balloting 
the socialists made it clear throughout the election campaign 
they would not form a coalition with the freedom party which they 
say is too far right 
preliminary results announced by interior minister franz 
loeschnak showed the freedom party increased its representation 
from 18 to 33 seats in the 183seat parliament and won 17 percent 
of the vote up from 10 percent in 1986 
the socialist party added one seat and now holds 81 
the big loser was the peoples party which has been in a 
coalition with the socialists since 1986 it lost 17 of its 77 
seats its worst defeat in history 
the fourth major party the green alternative won nine seats 
an increase of one 
freedom party leader joerg haider appealed to nationalist 
sentiments and voters seeking a change after 45 uninterrupted years 
of rule by either the socialists or the peoples party 
he hammered away at the special advantages members of the two 
big parties enjoy and attacked the relatively liberal treatment 
given immigrants from neighboring east european countries 
the charismatic 40yearold had said he hoped his party could 
win between 2530 seats with its campaign against bureaucracy and 
highlevel mismanagement 
