<TEXT>
a florida arms brokr is suing to recover more than 
30 million he claims is owed to him for arranging the sale of 
cluster bombs to iraq the timing his lawyer admits may be a 
little awkward 
nasser beydoun 47 of coral springs said he masterminded a 
1983 deal that enabled chilean industrialist carlos cardoen to sell 
the baghdad government at least 467 million worth of cluster bombs 
and other military equipment 
in a lawsuit filed with the circuit court in dade county 
beydoun claims cardoen often referred to him as a golden key to 
the middle east arms market 
when i opened the market he crossed the bridge and he burned 
it leaving me behind beydoun said 
cardoen 48 made a fortune selling bombs to iraq during its 
eightyear war with iran the miami herald reported saturday 
beydoun said he hooked up with cardoen in 1982 when he was 
appointed the exclusive sales representative of explosivos cardoen 
ltd in iraq lebanon and saudi arabia 
in court papers beydoun claimed he gave up a lucrative food and 
cigarette exporting business to work for cardoen whose cardoen 
industries operates a weapons factory in chile 
cardoen signed a letter of agreement and protection that 
authorized beydoun to be his exclusive agent in iraq court papers 
say 
beydouns job was to sell 500pound cluster bombs to the iraqi 
air force at 6500 apiece he was to receive 500 for each bomb 
sold 
beydoun said he spent 285000 of his own money to fly back and 
forth to baghdad the iraqis eventually agreed to buy 3000 cluster 
bombs at 7230 each he said 
cardoen sent the bombs overseas aboard an iraqi airways jet from 
santiago or by ship out of the chilean port of iquique beydoun 
said in court papers that sale put 21 million into cardoens bank 
accounts in dade county and elsewhere the lawsuit said 
the iraqis later purchased more bombs a bomb factory and 
machinery beydoun claims in the suit in all cardoen sold at 
least 467 million in war materials the suit says 
beydoun claims he is owed commissions of 359 million but has 
collected only 53 million 
beydouns attorney hendrik milne said his client tried to 
settle the dispute this summer cardoens lawyers have rejected the 
claims milne told the miami herald 
with iraqs invasion of kuwait and the buildup of us troops in 
saudi arabia a florida jury might find it difficult to side with 
someone who supplied bombs that could be used against americans 
milne said 
its not a popular case on either side he said 
on the other hand he said who are they going to prefer the 
bomb maker who kept all the money or the broker who should have 
been paid and wasnt 
