<TEXT>
moslem militants and indian security 
forces held running gun battles over a 12hour period sunday 
leaving 11 dead and fires allegedly set by militiamen destroyed 
100 houses news accounts said 
the army was deployed in downtown srinagar and the city 
administration imposed a curfew according to the reports from the 
press trust and united news of india news agencies 
srinagar the summer capital of jammu and kashmir state has 
been wracked since january by a moslem movement for secession from 
hindudominated india 
srinagar residents said indian paramilitary troops set fire to a 
residential neighborhood in retaliation for an early morning ambush 
by the militants the fire destroyed more than 100 wooden houses 
and spread to a downtown area 
security men came and threw gunpowder on my house and my 
window caught fire resident ghulam rasson gilkar said 
shouting and screams rose from the densely populated cowdara 
neighborhood about a mile from the city center as residents 
loaded whatever they could on their backs and fled to safety 
through narrow alleyways 
an indian government spokesman in new delhi denied soldiers set 
the blaze which he said was caused by gunfire the spokesman could 
not be identified under briefing regulations 
residents also told reporters that security forces had fired 
upon fire trucks that approached to douse the flames 
united news of india said gun battles sunday left nine civilians 
and two indian soldiers dead at least 12 people including five 
soldiers were injured the agency said 
militants also tried to assassinate izhar alam the 
secondranking police officer in kashmir their gunfire missed alam 
but critically wounded two of his guards the press trust reported 
at least 1340 people have died in political violence in kashmir 
this year indian security forces have been accused of human rights 
violations in trying to suppress the militant movement 
