<TEXT>
the soviet union has indicated it may be willing to 
return two of four disputed islands to japan to improve relations 
between the two countries news reports said sunday 
soviet officials made the proposal to a group of japanese 
lawmakers who visited moscow late last month japanese newspapers 
reported 
the territorial dispute involves the southern kuril islands off 
northern japan which were seized by the soviet union at the end of 
world war ii the dispute has prevented better ties between the two 
pacific powers and kept them from signing a peace treaty officially 
ending wartime hostilities 
the soviet officials proposed to the japanese delegation that 
the new agreement confirm a 1956 japansoviet joint declaration at 
the time moscow agreed to return shikotan island and the smaller 
habomai island group kyodo news service quoted japanese officials 
as saying 
the 1956 declaration cleared the way for a resumption of 
diplomatic relations but when japan signed a mutual security 
treaty with the united states in 1960 the soviet union declared it 
would only return the islands after all foreign troops were 
withdrawn from japan 
japan has continued to demand that all four of the disputed 
islands in the southern kurils be returned the other islands are 
kunashiri and etorofu 
the soviet union hopes that it can attract japanese investment 
and high technology assistance by settling the territorial dispute 
the nationally circulated newspaper asahi shimbun said soviet 
officials hoped to conclude the new agreement when soviet president 
mikhail gorbachev visits tokyo next spring 
asahi shimbun said the proposed agreement calls for the 
countries to cooperate in seeking international stability and 
development prepare for the conclusion of a peace treaty in three 
to five years confirm the principles of the 1956 joint 
declaration and increase economic cooperation and exchanges 
japanese government and party officials and soviet embassy 
officials were not available sunday to discuss the reports 
</TEXT>
