<TEXT>
the united auto workers reached a 
tentative national labor contract early sunday with ford motor co 
that apparently follows a pattern set in negotiations with general 
motors corp 
neither the union nor ford gave details of the new contract uaw 
president owen bieber however referred to similarities between 
the ford and gm pacts 
this tentative agreement provides that uawrepresented ford 
workers will fully share in the gains achieved by the pattern 
settlement reached earlier at general motors bieber said 
ford which relies more heavily on overtime than gm and chrysler 
corp was wary about a provision in the gm agreement that pays 
workers 5 an hour extra for excessive overtime 
other provisions of the uawgm pact likely to be carried over to 
ford include 
a 3percent increase in base wages in the first year of the 
contract 
lumpsum payments equal to 3 percent of wages in the second 
and third years 
continuation in costofliving adjustments for wages 
pension improvements 
no change in healthcare provisions 
the contract will be reviewed by the ford bargaining council on 
tuesday the council made up of presidents and bargaining 
committee heads at the uaws 79 local unions at ford plants and 
offices must approve it before the contract is sent out for 
ratification among fords 100000 uaw members 
jack hall fords chief negotiator said the contract has been 
achieved at a time when the competition in our industry has never 
been tougher the cyclical nature of our business is a hard fact of 
life and world events have heightened economic uncertainties 
in all uaw contracts with the big three cover more than 450000 
active workers 
the agreement with ford and its apparent similiarity with the 
gm contract puts additional pressure on chrysler where about 
60000 hourly and salaried workers are covered by the uaw contract 
the union has insisted that a contract it reaches with one of 
the companies will be the model for the other two chrysler has 
said the gm agreement appears to be very expensive 
</TEXT>
